li.p:
Let C be the set of calculus students and P the physics students.  Since all 30 students took at least one of the courses,,\lvert C \cup P\rvert = 30 and we can place a zero outside the circles in the Venn diagram to the left. 

\begin{split}
	30 = \mid C \cup P \mid &= \lvert C \rvert + \lvert  P \rvert - \lvert C \cap P\rvert\\
								&=18+12 - \lvert C \cap P\rvert 
	\end{split}
		which implies that C \cap P is empty.

If five students did not take either of the two courses, then\lvert C \cup P\rvert = 25 and
		\begin{split}
		25 = \lvert C \cup P \rvert &= \lvert C \rvert + \lvert  P \rvert - \lvert C \cap P\rvert\\
								&=18+12 - \lvert C \cap P\rvert \end{split}  
				which implies that \lvert C \cap P \rvert=5.
